.Dd May 4, 2026
.Dt OPEN 1
.Os "iOS"
.Sh NAME
.Nm open
.Nd open files, URLs, applications, and user activities on iOS
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl e
.Op Fl t
.Op Fl f
.Op Fl F
.Op Fl W
.Op Fl R
.Op Fl n
.Op Fl g
.Op Fl h
.Op Fl s Ar partial_SDK_name
.Op Fl u Ar URL
.Op Fl b Ar bundle_identifier
.Op Fl a Ar application
.Op Fl Fl header
.Op Fl Fl help
.Op Fl Fl unlock
.Op Fl Fl intent
.Op Fl Fl userActivity Ar type
.Op Fl Fl userActivityTitle Ar title
.Op Fl Fl userActivityWebpageURL Ar URL
.Op Fl Fl userActivityInfo Ar KEY=VALUE
.Op Fl Fl annotation Ar JSON
.Op Fl Fl env Ar VAR
.Op Fl Fl stderr Ar PATH
.Op Fl Fl stdout Ar PATH
.Ar
.Op Fl Fl args Ar arg1 ...
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
command opens files, directories, URLs, or applications on iOS using the
platform backends that actually exist on the device. When no application is
specified, LaunchServices is used to resolve the default handler.
.Pp
Compared with macOS, some options are redefined to match iOS semantics and
some unsupported AppKit or Finder behaviors are rejected explicitly.
.Pp
You can specify one or more file names or pathnames, interpreted relative to
the shell's current working directory, or one or more URLs.
.Pp
The options are as follows:
.Bl -tag -width "--userActivityWebpageURL"
.It Fl a\ \&application
Specifies the application to use for opening the file, URL, or user activity.
Application names are matched against the installed app's localized and item
names.
.It Fl b\ \&bundle_identifier
Specifies the bundle identifier for the application to use when opening the
file, URL, or user activity.
.It Fl e
Causes the file to be opened with TextEdit if
.Li com.apple.TextEdit
is available.
.Pp
On iOS this is copy-to-app editing:
.Bl -bullet -compact
.It
LaunchServices imports a copy into TextEdit
.It
edits do not write back to the original file
.It
successful opens print the imported destination path when LaunchServices
reports it
.El
.It Fl t
Causes the file to be opened with the default plain-text editor, as determined
via LaunchServices document binding resolution.
.Pp
On iOS this has the same copy-to-app editing semantics as
.Fl e .
.It Fl f
Reads input from standard input, writes it to a temporary plain-text file, and
opens the result in TextEdit. This still uses the iOS copy-to-app editing
model.
.It Fl F
Opens the application fresh by terminating the target app, clearing its Saved
Application State, and relaunching it.
.Pp
On iOS,
.Fl F
requires an explicit application target, such as
.Fl a ,
.Fl b ,
.Fl e ,
.Fl t ,
or
.Fl f .
.It Fl W
Causes
.Nm
to wait until explicitly launched applications exit.
.Pp
On iOS,
.Fl W
does not apply to implicit bare file or URL opens.
.It Fl R
Reveals the specified path in Filza.
.Pp
This option requires a usable
.Li com.tigisoftware.Filza
installation. The current iOS implementation is reveal/highlight only; it does
not provide a separate file-open viewer path through Filza.
.It Fl n
Requests a new scene for the target application.
.Pp
On iOS this means new-scene behavior, not a second process instance.
.It Fl g
Launches the target application suspended when the launch path goes through
FrontBoard.
.Pp
This option requires an explicit application target and is not supported with
.Fl Fl userActivity
on the current implementation.
.It Fl h
Searches header include and framework roots for matching header names, then
opens the resolved path or paths.
.It Fl s Ar partial_SDK_name
Limits
.Fl h
header search to SDK directories whose names contain the supplied substring.
.Pp
This filters the SDK-root portion of the search. Live non-SDK system roots are
still searched.
.It Fl Fl header
Long form of
.Fl h .
.It Fl Fl help
Prints usage help.
.It Fl u Ar URL
Opens the specified URL even if the string could also be interpreted as a file
path.
.It Fl Fl args
All remaining arguments are passed to the opened application as argv.
.Pp
These arguments are not opened or interpreted by
.Nm
itself.
.It Fl Fl env Ar VAR
Adds
.Ar VAR
to the environment of the launched application.
.Ar VAR
should be formatted NAME=VALUE or NAME.
.Pp
This option requires an explicit application or explicit user-activity target.
.It Fl Fl stdout Ar PATH
Launches the application with stdout connected to
.Ar PATH .
.Pp
This option requires an explicit application or explicit user-activity target.
.It Fl Fl stderr Ar PATH
Launches the application with stderr connected to
.Ar PATH .
.Pp
This option requires an explicit application or explicit user-activity target.
.It Fl Fl unlock
Requests device unlock for explicit FrontBoard launches.
.Pp
This option is only supported when the launch path goes through an explicit app
target.
.It Fl Fl intent
Requests the iOS LaunchIntent flag.
.Pp
This is a narrow launch flag for explicit app and user-activity launches. It is
not a generic Siri or App Intent runner.
.It Fl Fl userActivity Ar type
Opens the application for the specified
.Li NSUserActivity
type.
.Pp
When
.Fl a
or
.Fl b
is not supplied, the implementation resolves the target by LaunchServices and a
fallback scan of installed
.Pa Info.plist
declarations.
.Pp
This option does not accept file or URL operands on iOS.
.It Fl Fl userActivityTitle Ar title
Sets
.Li NSUserActivity.title
for the user-activity launch.
.Pp
Requires
.Fl Fl userActivity .
.It Fl Fl userActivityWebpageURL Ar URL
Sets
.Li NSUserActivity.webpageURL
for the user-activity launch.
.Pp
Requires
.Fl Fl userActivity .
.It Fl Fl userActivityInfo Ar KEY=VALUE
Adds a string entry to
.Li NSUserActivity.userInfo .
This option may be repeated.
.Pp
Requires
.Fl Fl userActivity .
.It Fl Fl annotation Ar JSON
Adds a property-list annotation payload for explicit-app URL and document opens.
JSON may be an object, array, string, number, true, false, or null.
.Pp
On iOS this is only supported for a single explicit-app file or URL operand.
.El
.Sh UNSUPPORTED OPTIONS
The following macOS options are currently unsupported on iOS and are rejected
with explicit diagnostics:
.Pp
.Bl -tag -width "-x"
.It Fl j
There is no meaningful app-hide equivalent in the current scope.
.It Fl x
There is no proven iOS equivalent for "do not add to recents".
.It Fl i
The
.Fl Fl stdin
path-launch option is not supported on iOS.
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
"open -b com.apple.Preferences" launches Settings by bundle identifier.
.Pp
"open -a TextEdit '/var/mobile/Documents/foo.txt'" imports the file into
TextEdit for editing.
.Pp
"printf 'hello\\n' | open -f" writes stdin to a temporary text file and opens it
in TextEdit using the iOS copy-to-app editing path.
.Pp
"open -R '/var/mobile/Documents/foo.txt'" launches Filza and highlights the
requested path.
.Pp
"open -h UIApplication.h" searches known iOS framework and SDK roots for the
header, then opens the resolved path in the current plain-text editor flow.
.Pp
"open -h -s iPhoneOS UIApplication.h" limits the SDK portion of header search
to SDK directories whose names contain
.Li iPhoneOS .
.Pp
"open --unlock -b com.apple.Preferences" requests an unlock-capable explicit
launch of Settings.
.Pp
"open --userActivity com.apple.TextEdit.editing -b com.apple.TextEdit" opens
TextEdit for the specified activity type.
.Pp
"open --annotation true -b com.example.MyApp '/var/mobile/Documents/foo.txt'"
opens the document explicitly in the named app with an annotation payload.
.Sh CAVEATS
The most important semantic differences from macOS are:
.Bl -bullet -compact
.It
.Fl e
and
.Fl t
are copy-to-app editing, not in-place editing
.It
.Fl n
means new scene, not new process
.It
.Fl W
only applies to explicitly launched applications
.It
.Fl R
uses Filza reveal on jailbroken iOS instead of Finder reveal
.El
.Sh HISTORY
The iOS implementation is a private-framework rewrite for AKCmds and preserves
the shell-facing behavior of macOS
.Nm
where iOS has a real equivalent.
